What's wrong: showing a toast and clearing the form forces the user to re-enter all their data just to fix one field. The server error contains field-specific information (field: 'postcode') that belongs inline next to the postcode field — not in a transient toast that disappears.

The correct implementation:

  onError: (error) => {
    if (error.field === 'postcode') {
      setError('postcode', {
        type: 'server',
        message: 'Invalid postcode for the selected country'
      });
    } else {
      setError('root', { message: 'Something went wrong. Please try again.' });
    }
  }

setError('postcode', ...) routes the error into RHF's field error state — it appears inline at errors.postcode.message without resetting or touching any other field values. The form stays open. The user sees exactly which field is wrong and why. The errors.root pattern handles non-field server errors (e.g. rate limit, server outage) that don't map to a specific field.

