Yes — the error path test typically needs to: (1) override the handler to return an error for the initial request, (2) assert the error UI appears, (3) restore the success handler before the retry click, (4) click retry, (5) assert the success UI appears.

The pattern to support this:

  it('shows error then retries successfully', async () => {
    const user = userEvent.setup();

    // Override to error for first request
    server.use(http.get('/api/projects', () => HttpResponse.error()));

    render(<ProjectList />, { wrapper: AppProviders });
    await screen.findByRole('alert');

    // Restore success handler before retry
    server.resetHandlers(); // removes the error override, restores default success handler

    await user.click(screen.getByRole('button', { name: /retry/i }));
    await screen.findAllByRole('listitem'); // success UI appears
  });

The key insight: server.resetHandlers() within a test (not just in afterEach) is valid and useful when you need to change server behavior mid-test to simulate a recovery scenario. This is a legitimate pattern, not a test smell.

