PART 1: CODE SPLITTING STRATEGY

Every byte of JavaScript shipped to the browser costs: download time, parse time, and execution time. Code splitting defers bytes not needed for the initial view.

TIER 1: ROUTE-LEVEL SPLITTING — the default
Every route is a potential split boundary because users navigate to one route at a time.

  const router = createBrowserRouter([
    {
      path: 'dashboard',
      lazy: () => import('./pages/Dashboard').then(m => ({ Component: m.default })),
    },
    {
      path: 'reports',   // Heavy: loads Recharts + TanStack Table
      lazy: () => import('./pages/Reports').then(m => ({ Component: m.default })),
    },
    {
      path: 'settings',
      lazy: () => import('./pages/Settings').then(m => ({ Component: m.default })),
    },
  ]);

Every route loads independently. The initial bundle contains only the shell, routing logic, and shared utilities.

TIER 2: COMPONENT-LEVEL SPLITTING — applied selectively
Rich text editors, PDF viewers, spreadsheet grids, large charting libraries can cost 200-500kb on their own.

  const RichTextEditor = React.lazy(() => import('./RichTextEditor'));
  const PdfViewer      = React.lazy(() => import('./PdfViewer'));

  function ContractEditor({ contract }: { contract: Contract }) {
    const [showPdf, setShowPdf] = useState(false);
    return (
      <FeatureErrorBoundary fallback={<EditorError />}>
        <Suspense fallback={<EditorSkeleton />}>
          <RichTextEditor initialContent={contract.body} />
        </Suspense>
        {showPdf && (
          <Suspense fallback={<PdfSkeleton />}>
            <PdfViewer url={contract.pdfUrl} />
          </Suspense>
        )}
      </FeatureErrorBoundary>
    );
  }

THE INTEGRATION WITH SECTION 2: Component-level splits use React.lazy + Suspense — exactly the async boundary system from Section 2. The split boundary IS a Suspense boundary. The fallback shown while the chunk downloads is the same mechanism as the fallback shown while data loads. Design them together.

WHEN NOT TO SPLIT:
- Small components (< 10kb) — HTTP request overhead exceeds savings.
- Components almost always needed on first visit.
- Components whose loading delay would be jarring without a suitable fallback.

PART 3: LIST VIRTUALIZATION

Rendering 10,000 DOM nodes blocks the main thread and makes scrolling janky. Virtualization renders only items visible in the viewport — typically 20-50 nodes — plus a small buffer.

WHEN NECESSARY:
- Lists of > ~200 items rendered simultaneously.
- Tables with many columns and many rows.
- Infinite scroll feeds without pagination.

WHEN PREMATURE:
- Paginated lists where each page has < 50 items — pagination already limits DOM size.
- Lists that never exceed 100 items in production.
- Lists with complex item heights where pagination is simpler.

TANSTACK VIRTUAL IMPLEMENTATION:
  function VirtualInvoiceList({ invoices }: { invoices: Invoice[] }) {
    const parentRef = useRef<HTMLDivElement>(null);
    const virtualizer = useVirtualizer({
      count:            invoices.length,
      getScrollElement: () => parentRef.current,
      estimateSize:     () => 72,  // estimated row height in px
      overscan:         5,         // render 5 items beyond visible area
    });

    return (
      <div ref={parentRef} style={{ height: '600px', overflow: 'auto' }}>
        <div style={{ height: virtualizer.getTotalSize(), position: 'relative' }}>
          {virtualizer.getVirtualItems().map(virtualItem => (
            <div
              key={virtualItem.key}
              style={{
                position:  'absolute',
                top:        0,
                transform: `translateY(${virtualItem.start}px)`,
                width:     '100%',
                height:    `${virtualItem.size}px`,
              }}
            >
              <InvoiceRow invoice={invoices[virtualItem.index]} />
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
    );
  }

THE PERFORMANCE MODEL: Without virtualization, 10,000 items = 10,000 DOM nodes. With virtualization, ~55 nodes at any time (50 visible + 5 overscan). The DOM node count stays constant regardless of list size.

VARIABLE HEIGHT ITEMS: Replace estimateSize with measureElement — TanStack Virtual measures each item after it renders and caches its actual size.

PART 4: RENDER OPTIMIZATION — MEMOIZATION DONE RIGHT

THE MEASUREMENT-FIRST RULE: Profile before memoizing. React DevTools Profiler shows component render durations. A component rendering in 0.3ms does not need memo — the comparison overhead may cost more.

CASES WHERE MANUAL MEMOIZATION EARNS ITS COST (even with the compiler):

  // 1. Genuinely expensive computation (e.g. 50ms)
  const processedData = useMemo(
    () => aggregateMetrics(rawEvents, dateRange),
    [rawEvents, dateRange]
  );

  // 2. Stable callback for a non-compiled third-party component
  const handleChange = useCallback(
    (value: string) => onFilterChange(value),
    [onFilterChange]
  );

  // 3. Stable object reference passed to a Context provider
  const contextValue = useMemo(
    () => ({ user, permissions }),
    [user, permissions]
  );

CASES THAT BECOME REDUNDANT WITH THE REACT COMPILER:
  // ❌ Redundant — compiler handles these
  const label   = useMemo(() => `${firstName} ${lastName}`, [firstName, lastName]);
  const onClick  = useCallback(() => setOpen(true), []);
  const MemoChild = React.memo(({ count }) => <span>{count}</span>);

THE COMPILER'S BLIND SPOTS:
  // Dynamic property access — not statically analysable
  const value = useMemo(() => config[dynamicKey], [config, dynamicKey]);

  // Side effect in render — impure, compiler skips
  function Component() {
    externalCache.set(id, value); // compiler skips this component entirely
    return <div />;
  }

If the compiler can't safely analyse a component, it silently skips it. Verify compiler coverage before removing manual memoizations.

feedback.elaborativeFeedback:
The problem: import { Editor } from '@company/rich-text' at the top of the route file is a static ES module import. The bundler resolves static imports at build time and includes them in the containing chunk. Even if you use React.lazy inside Settings.tsx, the static import in the route file means the 340kb is already bundled into whichever chunk contains the route file — React.lazy never gets to defer it because the module is already included.

The correct fix: remove the static import entirely and move the dynamic import inside the React.lazy call:

  // In Settings.tsx — NO static import of Editor
  const RichTextEditor = React.lazy(
    () => import('@company/rich-text').then(m => ({ default: m.Editor }))
  );

Now the dynamic import is the only reference to @company/rich-text in Settings.tsx. The bundler sees no static import to include in the Settings chunk — it creates a separate chunk for the 340kb editor that only downloads when RichTextEditor is first rendered.

The rule: a module can only be code-split if it is referenced only via dynamic import. Any static import of the same module forces it into the containing chunk.

isOverloaded is derived state. It is computed from the team member capacity data: isOverloaded = members.some(m => m.currentLoad / m.maxHours > 1.0). Storing it as useState creates the classic derived state synchronisation hazard: when capacity data updates (a task is reassigned via TanStack Query invalidation), the useState copy doesn't automatically update — there's a window where the banner shows the wrong state.

The correct mechanism: useMemo (or computed inline in the component):
  const isOverloaded = useMemo(
    () => members?.some(m => m.currentLoad / m.maxHours > 1.0) ?? false,
    [members]
  );

The consequences of storing it: (1) an overloaded team member gets their load reduced, TanStack Query refetches members, the new members array shows 0 overloaded — but the stored isOverloaded is still true until the next render triggers the effect. (2) If the effect is gated on members changing, it fires on the next render — so the bug window is one render cycle. Small but real, and unnecessary. (3) A developer reading the code sees two sources of truth and must reason about their synchronisation — increased cognitive load with no benefit.
